--- body ---
## Context

The autonomous beat agent (beat.py) runs on padme, but the pick-ticket Claude
instance has no knowledge of this. When a ticket body says "SSH to padme" or
"run on padme", pick-ticket treats it as an external dependency and skips the
ticket — even though it is already on padme.

Root cause: beat.py does not inject machine identity into the Claude invocation.

## Actions

1. In `~/.claude/scripts/beat.py`, add the hostname to the pick-ticket (and
   orchestrator) prompt. Options:
   a. Append to the `-p` skill argument: `f"/pick-ticket\n\nRunning on: {socket.gethostname()}"`
   b. Add a `BEAT_HOST` env var and reference it from the pick-ticket skill prompt
   c. Add a one-line system note in `beat-settings.json` (if it supports a system field)

2. Update the pick-ticket skill to use this context when assessing tickets:
   "SSH to <hostname>" is not a blocker if hostname matches.

3. Also check `--data-dir` stale paths: if a ticket specifies an explicit path
   that no longer exists, the agent should check whether the script has a working
   default before rejecting. Document this in the pick-ticket skill or beat-settings.

## Exit criteria

- A beat run on padme no longer skips tickets gated on "SSH to padme".
- pick-ticket skill documents the hostname-awareness rule.
